        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1987-06-05T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1987-06-05T00:00:00-05:00" n="366"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d366">
                <head>366. Evening Reading for President <persName corresp="#p_RRW_1"
                        >Reagan</persName>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d366fn1">Source: Department of State,
                        Environmental Issues, 1979–1993, Lot 93D395, Ozone. Drafted by <persName
                            corresp="#p_BRE_1">Benedick</persName> on June 5 and cleared by
                            <persName corresp="#p_NJD_1">Negroponte</persName> and <persName
                            corresp="#p_SRJ_1">Smith</persName>. There is no indication <persName
                            corresp="#p_RRW_1">Reagan</persName> saw this document.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date
                            ana="#date_undated-inferred-from-document-content" calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1987-06-05">undated</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>This is to alert you that the Domestic Policy Council (<gloss target="#t_DPC_1"
                        >DPC</gloss>) meets next week to consider U.S. policy in ongoing
                    international negotiations on protection of the stratospheric ozone layer.
                        <persName corresp="#p_WJC_1">John Whitehead</persName> will represent me.
                    Until now the U.S. has played a strong and widely acclaimed leadership role in
                    these talks. I have written <persName corresp="#p_MEE_1">Ed Meese</persName>
                    <note n="2" xml:id="d366fn2">See Tab A, Document 364.</note> of my strong belief
                    that a weakening of the U.S. negotiating position, as <pb facs="1091" n="1045"
                        xml:id="pg_1045"/> advocated by some agencies, would generate adverse
                    political reactions at home and abroad. Strong feelings in Congress<note n="3"
                        xml:id="d366fn3">See “Briefing: <persName corresp="#p_HDP_1"
                            >Hodel</persName> Catching the Heat; Tug of War on the Presidential
                        Debates; Crusade on Capital Gains,” <hi rend="italic">New York Times</hi>,
                        June 4, 1987, p. B8.</note> could lead to stringent unilateral U.S.
                    regulations, which would be far less desirable for U.S. industry and consumers
                    than a global accord. A retreat could also undermine our credibility in the area
                    of international environmental protection when in fact this negotiation presents
                    an excellent opportunity for the Administration to score a significant success
                    in this field.</p>
            </div>
